SIMPLE: farthing
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Farthing
<hw>Far"thing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>furthing</ets>, AS. <ets>fe⟦oacute⟧r⟦edh⟧ung</ets>, fr.
<ets>fe⟦oacute⟧r⟦edh⟧a</ets> fourth, <ets>fe⟦oacute⟧r</ets>,
<ets>fe⟦oacute⟧wer</ets>, four. See <er>Four</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The fourth of a penny; a small copper coin of Great Britain, being
a cent in United States currency.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A very small quantity or value.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In her cup was no <qex>farthing</qex> seen of grease.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A division of land.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thirty acres make a <qex>farthing</qex> land; nine
<qex>farthings</qex> a Cornish acre; and four Cornish acres a knight's
fee.</q> <rj><qau>R. Carew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Farthingale</ent>⟦br⟧
